        <span class="item-tag">Fiction &middot; Short story</span>
        <h1>Blind Tracks</h1>
        <p class="story-byline">By Alexandros Emmanouilidis</p>
        <p class="story-recognition">
          Third place, University of Cyprus Student Club Literary Competition, 2026.
          Set in the same original fantasy world as <a href="/portfolio/the-world">Zeton</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <hr class="divider" />

      <div class="story-body">
        <p>Rain hammered the world the color of old blood. Crimson lightning spidered across the sky. The stone crouched at the hill's base. It was cold to the touch. Everything felt wrong.</p>

        <p>Taren felt the storm as pressure first, then as a slow, glassy hush that smothered ordinary sound. Rain braided into wind and wind braided into light. Somewhere, the convoy's route folded into ghost-creases on the map of the day.</p>

        <p>He said it aloud, once, small enough to be a vow and a confession: "I went after her." The words vanished into the gale. Lira had not come back with the convoy. The chief had told him to wait. Waiting felt like burying her before the ground had finished deciding. He had taken his Boncha mount, broad-backed and well-cared for, and cut through the village's gates while his name was still being shouted.</p>

        <p>There was no argument left to make to the sky. He hunched into the wind, jaw locked and shoulders tight, taking its blows one breath at a time until the drum in his throat drowned everything else.</p>

        <p>Taren closed his eyes.</p>

        <p>"The protocols are clear. Two full cycles." The chief's voice had the weight of carved stone. "We cannot risk a search party."</p>

        <p>"There isn't time." Taren held his hands together so they wouldn't show the shake. "Harvest season is done. Mud smears the roads, everyone knows that. We won't find their tracks."</p>

        <p>"I said we hold, boy," the chief had said dismissively.</p>

        <p>Taren could still taste the gate-mud in the air from where they'd hauled Gáldri, the convoy's leader, through the gate - soaked, torn, and barely alive.</p>

        <p><em>If Lira's alive,</em> Taren said to himself. <em>I have to find her. Waiting is choosing not to.</em> He met the chief's eyes and saw only the patient mercy of rules meant for people who still had time.</p>

        <p>The sky darkened by degrees.</p>

        <p>The ordinary gray soaked to wine, the wine to crimson, and then a cold indigo rose from beneath like deep water coming up to meet the light. Lightning stitched behind the lid of cloud without yet breaking. The air felt thick - strange even - despite the wind.</p>

        <p>Rain slanted; wind hit in straight, measured blows. Taren set his feet too wide, then too narrow, shoulders braced, then forced loose - constantly second-guessing - trying to be the shape the storm might overlook.</p>

        <p>The first strike landed close - thick as poured metal. That wasn't weather. That was the Dream. The shockwave slapped him sideways. Mud bit his hands. The sound was wrong too - less a crack than a tearing of pressure. Taren turned in time to see a lone tree twist and change - its branches folding in on themselves, then snapping down into knuckle-fists; roots unearthing from the ground and knotting into a black cage. For one long breath the tree held that unnatural pose - then collapsed into dust.</p>

        <p>The hilltop bucked under Taren's boots. His stomach lifted like he'd missed a step.</p>

        <p>Pressure. Tilt. Breath.</p>

        <p>His vision steadied. The same tree - or not the same - unstuck and small, huddled against the slope. Taren sat with his back to its thin trunk, cloak hooded, the mem-map open across his knees, tracing the river's broken line with a careful, mud-stained finger. Rain beaded on the waxed cloth.</p>

        <p>The Boncha mount, tied to the tree, snorted and pawed, four heavy legs thudding the mud.</p>

        <p>"What?" Taren managed a thin smile. "I remember it. It'll hold." He'd copied this map himself - ridge by ridge, wash by wash - knowing memory-ink kept only what the mind could keep. A mem-map didn't record the land; it recorded the remembering of it. Forget a turn, and the line thinned. Doubt it, and the ink went to mist. Sometimes the world did the same.</p>

        <p>Far out on the flats, a herd ran - low, many-legged, flowing like spilled beads. Banchalas. He'd only ever traced their shapes on some hunter's old chart; seeing them here meant the Banchala plains weren't far. Close to the river, then. Close to where the convoy should have cut through.</p>

        <p>"We're not far off, buddy." He rose, fed the Boncha a twist of dried root, and rubbed its jaw until the eye softened. The creature's attention fixed on the distant run, as if some kin-memory tugged. Banchalas and Bonchas - same blood once, now bent different.</p>

        <p>He thought of how the world reformed what it needed. Banchalas into Bonchas. Straight rivers into wash scars. And people, too. Lira, much like the majority of people, had the Dream like a lit wick - chosen, attuned, seen. But the world also forcefully left a few unlit on purpose. Nulls, born with no spark for the Dream to catch. Taren was one of them. The Dream always seemed to go around him. He used to think that made him useless. Out here, it might be the only reason he could still stand.</p>

        <p>He folded the mem-map to keep the memory bright, palmed the mount's warm cheek, and breathed once to measure the distance between names and loss.</p>

        <p>"Hold on," he said to the wind, to her, to the line he refused to let fade. "I'll find you. I promise."</p>

        <p>Stone. Wind. Crimson. Nothing.</p>

        <p>Pressure gathered like a hand around Taren's ribs. Lightning moved under the indigo lid and the storm's mouth opened wider, hunting for anything that would answer back.</p>

        <p>The wind came in hard. Blows stepped him left, then right, then almost to his knees. Rain ran in cords across his face. He tried to widen his stance, again, trying to resist the irresistible. But not to his surprise, the body seemed to have its own opinions about balance and fear.</p>

        <p>Taren slipped, caught himself, and understood why he'd cut the gate against the chief's patience. Not because Nulls could brave what others could not, but because he needed a shape to stand in - find them, find her, and let that be worth, let that mark his purpose.</p>

        <p>His vision blurred for a moment. The stone waited, its curved lines drawing the world inward. If such a storm formed here, the convoy might not be gone so much as misplaced. Hope was a thin wire, but it ran when struck. Left - right - breath - eyes salt-stung and blinking.</p>

        <p>"Hold, Taren!" He could almost hear Lira's voice say it - steady, teasing. He held. The storm licked around him, searching for a seam in what he was. Its energy slid off. Wind and rain did not.</p>

        <p>Another shove, a near-fall, the hill rolling underfoot like a thrown shoulder. Taren planted his feet and tried again. He had never felt so alone. He had never felt so exactly himself.</p>

        <p>Tilt. Sound. Pressure.</p>

        <p>Lira's voice, old as muscle-memory: <em>Loosen your shoulders. Let the world go around you where it can't go through. Not everything deserves an answer.</em></p>

        <p>Taren wanted to believe her. He wanted a doorway that belonged to him and not to fear, not to rules that fit everyone else.</p>

        <p>He felt his jaw lock. He released it. He let breath sit low and plain in his chest.</p>

        <p>Stone. Wind. Crimson. Something.</p>

        <p>The hill pitched and settled under the storm's weight. Rain sheeted sideways; Wind still hit in clean counting blows. Taren set his jaw, the way Lira had told him - then loosened his shoulders, let the gale slide where it couldn't bite, let breath be a quiet held cup. The Dream searched him and found nothing to take.</p>

        <p>Taren opened his eyes. Indigo sky. Maroon veins. The storm's coil searching.</p>

        <p>"Go around me," he muttered, and this time it wasn't defiance. It was design.</p>

        <p>The storm worked at him like a craftsman. Wind hit in hard. Rain shoved at him until his knees wanted to fold. Lightning cracked close enough to make his teeth ache. The coil prowled the flats, then climbed, patient as a hunter, dragging its weight so the hill's crown leaned towards its mouth.</p>

        <p>He felt it like a stone feels a river: pressure, direction, no invitation. The storm wanted him the way the Dream wants any shape that wanders - wants to move, to echo, to wear a curve into it. But Null meant there was no echo to fetch. It slid around him. Wind could push flesh. Rain could wet skin. The rest - color, pressure, the mind's easy yielding to the great - found no purchase.</p>

        <p>He set his jaw. He loosened his shoulders. He held his breath quiet and ordinary in his chest.</p>

        <p>Rain still fell. Wind still blew. But the pull - that low, old wish of the Dream to take and keep - went around him like water parted by a prow of a boat.</p>

        <p>He moved, slow and deliberate, off his crest. The coil worried the ridge behind him; lightning stitched the sky above. He kept the stance Lira had pressed into him and stepped down toward the marker he'd named in his head. He had seen it before.</p>

        <p>The stone squatted at the base of the wrong-steep slope, wet as bone. Up close its surface was unsettling to the eye. Lines like quick writing, wild and cursive, etched inward from every edge. All of it flowed toward a puckered strike at the center, where lightning seemed to have punched and then remained. The air was even heavier there, as if sound had been made dense and stacked until it pointed inward.</p>

        <p>He raised his hand. Rain drummed his knuckles. The world pressed its case.</p>

        <p>Taren set his fingers to the mark where all the quick lines met.</p>

        <p>The instant he touched the center, everything stopped. Wind, rain, the cursed, indigo color. Gone. As the sky thinned, the two moons appeared - one crimson and bright, the other pale and cold. Everything that happened felt like a dream.</p>

        <p>Hooves. Voices. Almost real.</p>

        <p>He turned, too quickly, heart climbing into his mouth. A line of Bonchas poured across the flats and shouldered up the hill, the convoy in a weary living thread. Lira swung down first, boots in the wet grass, her face bright with disbelief.</p>

        <p>"Taren? What in the world are you doing here?"</p>

        <p>Taren grabbed her shoulders in disbelief. She was warm. His hands wouldn't stop shaking.</p>

        <p>"I came to find you." His voice broke on the last word as if he'd run a long way inside it. "You weren't back when you were supposed to, and Gáldri -"</p>

        <p>"Gáldri what?" she said, already half-turning, and there he was on his mount a few lengths behind, wet and very alive, raising a hand in apology for being exactly where he shouldn't have been if Taren's fear were true.</p>

        <p>"Taren, what is happening?"</p>

        <p>He didn't answer. He understood. He stepped into her and held on like a sailor finding a post, every question collapsing against relief. Her hair was wet, but the water never dripped. She felt so real, yet so distant. Taren closed his eyes.</p>

        <p>When he opened them, he could see the hill the way it should have been: the tree not scoured to dust, only small and wet; the slope merely steep, not wrong; the sky still and moving. The stone under his palm was cold. The hooves and voices were not there. Lira wasn't there.</p>

        <p>He hadn't moved. Not really. His fingers hadn't even flexed. The stone showed a motivation. His breath came back to him as sound.</p>

        <p>No roar. No tearing pressure. Just rain, small and steady, and the soft shift of grass under his boots.</p>

        <p>Taren's hand was still on the inward mark. The stone sat quiet beneath his palm, the lines dead-still, like they'd never moved at all.</p>

        <p>He now understood: being a Null was not lack. It was contour. It was the shape by which wild things moved and could not move.</p>

        <p>He took his hand away. The world didn't argue with him. It simply continued - around, past him, around him.</p>

        <p>And in that continuing, he noticed what he'd missed: not tracks - rain killed those - but the absence of them. A drag in the grass. He dropped to one knee and ran two fingers through the grass. Water beaded everywhere - except along a narrow line, a path guarded by the wind. As if that line had been forgotten.</p>

        <p>He was one step closer to finding Lira. And this time he knew who he was - what he was - and how to use himself to find the one he loved.</p>

        <p>Taren stood, stepped into the thin line and followed the blind tracks.</p>
